          <span class="ba-label">#9 · $45–$3,600/MO · 4/6 PIPELINE STEPS</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">HubSpot Content Hub — Best for inbound marketing + content in one platform</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">For HubSpot CRM users who want to manage blog, landing pages, and content analytics inside the platform they already use for sales and marketing.</p>
        </div>
        <p style="color: var(--text-2); margin: 0 0 20px;">HubSpot Content Hub is worth considering only if you're already in the HubSpot ecosystem. The CMS is genuinely good, the AI writing tools are improving, and having content analytics connected to your CRM is a real advantage. But the price scales fast — the Content Hub starts at $45/month and reaches $3,600/month for enterprise. And the content creation quality lags behind dedicated tools.</p>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>Native CRM integration — content and pipeline in one view</h4><p>Content attribution to deals and pipeline is the strongest case for HubSpot. If you run account-based marketing, this is genuinely useful.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>CMS, SEO tools, and analytics in one platform</h4><p>Eliminates the WordPress + Semrush + Google Analytics stack for teams that want everything under one login.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>AI writing tools inside the content editor</h4><p>HubSpot's Breeze AI generates blog drafts, meta descriptions, and social posts from within the platform.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✗</span><div><h4>Honest con: price and content quality both miss</h4><p>The Pro tier ($800/month) is required for most serious content features. At that budget, you could run theStacc ($99) plus a full SEO tool suite and still come out ahead on both output and cost.</p></div></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="ba-grid" id="service-10" style="margin-top: 48px;">
      <div class="ba-col before" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <div class="ba-head">
          <span class="ba-label">#10 · $10–$24/SEAT/MO · 2/6 PIPELINE STEPS</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">Monday.com — Best project management layer for large content teams</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">For large content organizations that need to manage dozens of writers, deadlines, and approvals — and want to overlay AI task automation on top of their existing process.</p>
        </div>
        <p style="color: var(--text-2); margin: 0 0 20px;">Monday.com is a project management platform, not a content workflow tool. It can be configured to manage a content pipeline — deadline tracking, writer assignments, approval stages — but it doesn't write, optimize, or publish anything. The AI features are basic workflow automations (auto-assign tasks, auto-update statuses). Two of six steps, both focused on coordination rather than production.</p>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>Highly flexible pipeline configuration</h4><p>You can build any content workflow — brief → draft → review → publish — with custom statuses, automations, and views. More flexible than any dedicated content tool.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>Good for large teams with complex dependencies</h4><p>Managing 20+ writers with different deadlines, editors, and approval chains is where Monday.com outperforms dedicated content platforms.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>Affordable per-seat pricing</h4><p>At $10–$24/seat, it's cheaper than any dedicated content tool at scale for large teams.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✗</span><div><h4>Honest con: you still need every other tool in the stack</h4><p>Monday.com manages the workflow — it doesn't run it. You still need writers, SEO tools, CMS publishing, and editorial resources. The tool cost is low; the total system cost is high.</p></div></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

