  <!-- BUYER'S GUIDE -->
  <section class="problem-section">
    <div class="problem-header">
      <span class="label-pill">Buyer's guide</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">What to look for in an <span class="accent">automated content workflow tool.</span></h2>
      <p>If you're shopping outside this list, here's the scorecard we'd use ourselves.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ba-grid">
      <div class="ba-col after" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">01</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Count the pipeline steps — then count the handoffs</h4>
              <p>A tool that covers 5 of 6 steps with 4 manual handoffs is worse than a tool that covers 3 steps with 1 handoff. The goal is eliminating the time between steps, not just the number of tools.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">02</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Demand a direct CMS publishing integration — not an export</h4>
              <p>Manual CMS upload is the most underestimated time cost in any content workflow. A 30-article/month operation with manual publishing costs 15–30 hours per month just in copy-paste work.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">03</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Calculate cost per published article — not cost per month</h4>
              <p>A $49/month tool that produces 4 articles costs $12.25 per article. A $99/month service that produces 30 costs $3.30 per article. The monthly sticker price is almost always the wrong number to compare.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">04</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Ask if you need editorial control — or just output</h4>
              <p>Teams with a managing editor and brand standards need approval workflows. Solo operators and small businesses that just need consistent SEO content published don't — and paying for approval features they won't use is wasted spend.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">05</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Test with competitive keywords, not easy ones</h4>
              <p>Any AI content tool can produce a passable article on a zero-competition keyword. What separates the field is performance on keywords with 10+ competing pages already ranking. Test there before you commit.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

